SIMPLE: hover
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hover
<hw>Hov"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Etymol.
doubtful.]</ety> <def>A cover; a shelter; a protection.</def>
<mark>[Archaic]</mark> <rj><au>Carew.</au> <au>C.
Kingsley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hover</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hover
<hw>Hov"er</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Hovered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hovering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>hoveren</ets>, and
<ets>hoven</ets>, prob. orig., to abide, linger, and fr. AS.
<ets>hof</ets> house; cf. OFries. <ets>hovia</ets> to receive into one's
house. See <er>Hovel</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To hang fluttering in
the air, or on the wing; to remain in flight or floating about or over a
place or object; to be suspended in the air above something.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Great flights of birds are <qex>hovering</qex> about the bridge,
and settling on it.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>hovering</qex> mist came swimming o'er his sight.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To hang about; to move to and fro near a place,
threateningly, watchfully, or irresolutely.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Agricola having sent his navy to <qex>hover</qex> on the
coast.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Hovering</qex> o'er the paper with her quill.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>hoya</ent>⟦br⟧
